R/Bioconductor tools for reproducible proteomics data analysis

Laurent Gatto

11/5/2018

Find this documet at https://github.com/lgatto/2018_11_05_RBiocProt_DDUV

Introduction

  1. Use case: Quantitative MS-based spatial proteomics (intro from https://zenodo.org/record/1435058).
  2. Data structure.

Demo

Missing data

data(naset)
naplot(naset)

plot of chunk na

filterNA(naset, pNA = 0.5) %>%
    naplot

plot of chunk na

naset %>%
    filterNA( pNA = 0.5) %>%
    impute(method = "knn") %>%
    naplot

plot of chunk na

res <- naset %>%
    filterNA( pNA = 0.5) %>%
    impute(method = "knn")

Normalisation

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
boxplot(exprs(res))

res %>%
    normalise(method = "vsn") %>%
    exprs %>%
    boxplot
## vsn2: 677 x 16 matrix (1 stratum).

Offline

pRoloc documentation: http://lgatto.github.io/pRoloc/

Gatto L, Lilley KS. MSnbase-an R/Bioconductor package for isobaric tagged mass spectrometry data visualization, processing and quantitation. Bioinformatics. 2012 Jan 15;28(2):288-9. doi: 10.1093/bioinformatics/btr645. Epub 2011 Nov 22. PubMed PMID: 22113085.

MSnbase documentation: http://lgatto.github.io/MSnbase/

Gatto L, Christoforou A. Using R and Bioconductor for proteomics data analysis. Biochim Biophys Acta. 2014 Jan;1844(1 Pt A):42-51. doi: 10.1016/j.bbapap.2013.04.032. Epub 2013 May 18. Review. PubMed PMID: 23692960.
